alternatives.transcript: hello mister palmer is a sixty two year old male who presented today with dyspnea and fatigue after being referred to us by his family doctor he noticed fatigue and dyspnea while walking two weeks ago although he states that it is better with rest and better with laying down the dyspnea and fatigue became worse last night and he also reports a history of presyncope palpitations and wheezing he has a medical history of hypertension for which he takes lisinopril and he takes no other medications he has no allergies he had a cardiac cath years ago which came back normal and he also has a family medical history of sudden death in his mother at forty his father died of an mi in his fifties he is an elementary school teacher who drinks one cup of coffee a day no alcohol no tobacco and he eats a balanced diet and he enjoys going for walks every day although he has been unable to do this recently due to the dyspnea and fatigue for his vitals i noticed a heart rate of one hundred and ten oxygen saturation of ninety six blood pressure of one thirty over ninety and a respiratory rate of sixteen and a temperature of ninety eight on physical exam i noted a crescendo decrescendo murmur and a displaced pmi which i discussed with the patient for his imaging on the x-ray we saw a cardiomyopathy and cardiomegaly on the echo we saw hypertrophy of the septum and on the ekg showed septal hypertrophy with increased amplitude waves in the leads v one v two and v three so the diagnosis which i think is most likely for his case is familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy which i discussed with the patient and i prescribed disopyramide for him and discontinued his lisinopril i also referred him to an interventional cardiologist which i discussed with the patient and as a cardiovascular serotonin thank you
